olive oil
1 portion cauliflower
1 carrot
1 packet beef mince
1 packet basmati rice
1 sachet beef-style stock powder
¼ tsp salt
1 cucumber
3 clove garlic
1 packet Bengal Curry Paste
1 sachet Mumbai Spice Blend
1 packet Greek-Style Yoghurt
1 sachet Brown Mustard Seeds
1.5 cup water

Preheat oven to 220ºC/200ºC fan-forced. Finely chop garlic. Cut cauliflower into small florets. Roughly chop carrot. Place cauliflower and carrot on a lined oven tray. Drizzle with olive oil, season with salt and toss to coat. Spread out evenly, then roast until tender and brown around the edges, 20-25 minutes.

SPICY! The curry paste is mild, but use a little less
if you're sensitive to heat.

Meanwhile, heat a large
saucepan over medium-high heat with a drizzle
of olive oil. Cook beef mince, breaking up with
a spoon, until just browned, 3-4 minutes. Add
Bengal curry paste, Mumbai spice blend, brown
mustard seeds and 1/2 the garlic and cook,
stirring, until fragrant, 1 minute.

Add basmati rice, beef-style stock powder and the salt to the pan and stir to coat. Add the water, then bring to the boil. Cover with a lid and reduce the heat to medium-low. Cook for 10 minutes, then remove the pan from heat and keep covered until rice is tender and the water is absorbed, 10 minutes.

TIP: The rice will finish cooking in its own steam so don't peek!

While the rice is cooking, finely chop cucumber. In a small frying pan, heat a drizzle of olive oil over medium-high heat. Cook remaining garlic until fragrant, 1 minute. Transfer garlic oil to a small bowl, then add Greek-style yoghurt and cucumber and stir to combine. Season to taste.

Add roasted veggies to the biryani and stir to combine.

Divide beef and cauliflower biryani between bowls. Top with cucumber raita to serve.